node.text:
The Flatworm 😵‍💫
Presently, there are approximately 20,000 species of flatworms! 
Flatworms usually feed on tunicates, small crustaceans, worms, and mollusks.
Their life cycle is not definite. However, some species are known to have lived for between 65 to 140 days.
In sexual reproduction, flatworms can either produce and fertilize their own eggs (since they are hermaphroditic) or mate with fellow flatworms (their skin absorbs sperms so minimal physical contact is required). After mating, the cocoon is released into the environment, which later develops with time and then hatches.

Filmed by Marcelo Johan Ogata @_bugdreamer_

node.text:
Any nickname ideas? 🐙 
🎥 : @mbari_news
🥞 Check out this Pokémon-looking flapjack octopus gliding through freezing water with its ear-like fins guiding the way! 🛸 

🚫Unlike most octopuses, the flapjack can't change colors. 

😎 Despite this fact, the flapjack octopus' camouflage is so effective that predators STILL can't spot them! 🤔

🤓 You see...Deep-sea animals that have red/orange bodies appear black to predators and prey because red light does not reach ocean depths! 🔴⚫️ 

💧 If water at just 5ft (1.52m) deep loses noticeable red light, imagine a flapjack octo chilling out in depths of 7,700ft (2,346m)!

🥶 And when we say chilling, we mean freezing...it’s 34-39 degrees F (1-4 degrees C) down there! Brrrr. 🥰 If ya read this far comment adorabilis below! 
🤩 The flapjack octopus is described as "so cute and adorable that the scientists initially wanted to name it octopus 'adorabilis'".

Think it’s adorable too? Share this cutie to your stories & show your friends! 
📚 Scientific Name: Opisthoteuthis
Via @octonation 💙🐙

node.text:
Tiny @underwater hands 🖐!!
Aka Polyps Coral.
Coral polyps are tiny, soft-bodied organisms related to sea anemones and jellyfish. At their base is a hard, protective limestone skeleton called a calicle, which forms the structure of coral reefs. Reefs begin when a polyp attaches itself to a rock on the sea floor, then divides, or buds, into thousands of clones.
🎥 @scubahai_nz
#ocean #sea #coral
